FIFA Ratings - Explored and Explained

Keith J. Mitchell

Project Description

The purpose of my project is to analyze a dataset related to either credit card fraud detection or player performance in FIFA 22. Haven't actually decided yet, but both would be pretty interesting. One is related to professional data in my field of study while the other is related to a hobby of mine that would be fascinating to deal with more under the hood data.

Objectives:

  1. Credit Card Fraud Detection:

    • Develop models to identify fraudulent transactions.
    • Explore features that indicate fraud.

  2. FIFA 22 Complete Player Dataset:

    • Analyze factors influencing player ratings.
    • Examine rating variations across positions.

  3. Video Game Sales Dataset:

    • Examine how global video game sales vary across different genres and platforms, focusing on trends in consumer preferences.
    • Analyze various sources of sales data (e.g., platform performance, genre popularity, release year) and statistics such as total sales to understand the composition of sales across different platforms and genres.

The final objective will focus on the FIFA 22 Complete Player Dataset, aiming to leverage data analysis techniques to uncover insights about player ratings. Specifically, the goal is to analyze the dataset to investigate potential biases in how ratings are assigned to players. Potential bias could be based on their positions, attributes, nationalities, various other influences in the dataset. This analysis will help determine whether certain player characteristics disproportionately influence their ratings, allowing for a deeper understanding of the rating system and its fairness across different player types.

Datasets and Questions

Dataset 1: Credit Card Fraud Detection

  • Description: The dataset contains transactions made by credit cards in September 2013 by European cardholders. This dataset presents transactions that occurred over two days, with 492 fraud cases out of 284,807 total transactions. The dataset is highly unbalanced, with the positive class (frauds) accounting for only 0.172% of all transactions.

  • Question: How can we effectively predict whether a transaction is fraudulent based on the transaction's features, and which features contribute the most to the detection of fraud?

Dataset 2: FIFA 22 Complete Player Dataset

  • Description: This dataset includes detailed information about players in FIFA 22, encompassing player data such as rating, position, skill moves, work rates, and physical stats. The dataset allows for analysis of player performance, comparisons across positions, and identification of trends in player statistics.

  • Question: What factors most significantly influence a player's rating, and how do these factors vary across different positions in the game? How do ratings change depending on position, and could there be some bias or skew in this dataset?

Dataset 3: Video Game Sales Dataset

  • Description: This dataset provides comprehensive information on video game sales across various platforms and genres. It includes data on global sales, release years, and ratings, enabling analysis of sales trends, popularity of genres, and the impact of platform differences on sales figures. The dataset allows for exploration of the gaming industry's landscape and insights into consumer preferences.

  • Question: How do global video game sales vary across different genres and platforms, and what factors contribute to these variations?

Dataset 1: Credit Card Fraud Detection

This project utilizes a dataset of credit card transactions from European cardholders collected in September 2013, containing nearly 285,000 entries, of which only 492 are labeled as fraudulent. As seen in the graph below, this an incredibly small figure, making the solution to the dataset questions that much more difficult. The dataset also includes various features such as transaction amount and time, designed to help identify fraudulent activity. It was chosen for its relevance to cybersecurity, allowing exploration of questions like, What features indicate fraud? and How can models predict fraudulent transactions? The dataset is sourced from a reputable Kaggle competition, ensuring data quality. However, the significant class imbalance presents challenges, as fraud accounts for only a small percentage of transactions. The goal is to develop effective models for fraud detection while recognizing and addressing potential biases in the data.

The histogram used in the previous section was super resourceful, showing the spread of player ratings. It revealed that most players fall with a certain range of ratings (60-70), making for a rough looking bell-curve. Few players are on the extreme high or low ends.

Next we can compare these ratings by position to attempt to get some more useful information from the rating category. This can be done with a dot plot as seen below. It illustrates the average player rating based on their primary position. There are some outliers from the norm. These may prove key to look into.

In[61]:
# Calculate average rating by primary position (first position)
average_ratings = fifa22_df['player_positions'].str.split(',').str[0].str.strip()
average_rating_by_position = fifa22_df.groupby(average_ratings)['overall'].mean().reset_index()

# Create the scatter plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
plt.scatter(average_rating_by_position['overall'], average_rating_by_position['player_positions'], color='blue', alpha=0.7)

plt.title('Average Player Ratings by Primary Position', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Average Overall Rating', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Primary Position', fontsize=14)
plt.grid(axis='x', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

plt.xlim(40, 90)  # Adjust limits based on rating range
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Conclusion

In this milestone, I have selected the FIFA 22 Complete Player dataset for my project, focusing on its potential to uncover insights into player performance and rating determination. This dataset presents an exciting opportunity to analyze various player metrics, explore trends, and examine factors that influence player ratings across different positions.

One of my motivations for choosing this dataset is my personal interest in sports and gaming, which makes the analysis more engaging and enjoyable. This motivation makes for a more enjoyable dive into the data and extraction of more meaningful insights to me personally. I believe that understanding what contributes to successful player performance can provide valuable perspectives for both a gaming and sports perspective, as well as allowing me to further my data science skills. It is a fairly complete dataset that can be easily manipulated for my needs.

As I began exploring the dataset, the information became noticeable as player ratings, attributes, positions, etc are all available and clearly labeled. The analysis can yield characteristics that define successful athletes, as well as the variations in ratings based on different playing positions amongst other things.

Furthermore, the findings from this analysis could resonate with quite a wide audience, appealing to gamers, coaches, and sports. Overall, I am excited and happy with my choice. We shall see what awaits us in the csv...
